09027nam a22020295i 9780691232461DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021035091  a97806912324617 a10.1515/97806912324612doi  a(DE-B1597)612397  a(OCoLC)1261773715  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aNB212.5.M63 4aNB212.5.M63bS85 2022 7aART0260002bisacsh04a731.0973/09042231 aSullivan, Marin R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAlloys :bAmerican Sculpture and Architecture at Midcentury /cMarin R. Sullivan. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b25 color + 125 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue The Architectural Requirements of Space -- tIntroduction Alloying Space -- t1 The Space Above -- t2 Dividing Space -- t3 The Space Between -- tEpilogue Preserving Space(s) -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tPhotography and Copyright Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA new look at the interrelationship of architecture and sculpture during one of the richest periods of American modern designAlloys looks at a unique period of synergy and exchange in the postwar United States, when sculpture profoundly shaped architecture, and vice versa. Leading architects such as Gordon Bunshaft and Eero Saarinen turned to sculptors including Harry Bertoia, Alexander Calder, Richard Lippold, and Isamu Noguchi to produce site-determined, large-scale sculptures tailored for their buildings’ highly visible and well-traversed threshold spaces. The parameters of these spaces—atriums, lobbies, plazas, and entryways—led to various designs like sculptural walls, ceilings, and screens that not only embraced new industrial materials and processes, but also demonstrated art’s ability to merge with lived architectural spaces.Marin Sullivan argues that these sculptural commissions represent an alternate history of midcentury American art. Rather than singular masterworks by lone geniuses, some of the era’s most notable spaces—Philip Johnson’s Four Seasons Restaurant in Mies van der Rohe’s Seagram Building, Max Abramovitz’s Philharmonic Hall at Lincoln Center, and Pietro Belluschi and Walter Gropius’s Pan Am Building—would be diminished without the collaborative efforts of architects and artists. At the same time, the artistic creations within these spaces could not exist anywhere else. Sullivan shows that the principle of synergy provides an accurate framework to assess this pronounced relationship between sculpture and architecture. She also explores the afterlives of these postwar commissions in the decades since their construction.A fresh consideration of sculpture’s relationship to architectural design and functionality following World War II, Alloys highlights the affinities between the two fields and the ways their connections remain with us today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aModernism (Art)zUnited States. 0aSculpture and architecturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSculpture, Americany20th century. 0aSite-specific sculpturezUnited Statesy20th century. 7aART / Sculpture & Installation.2bisacsh  a666 Fifth Avenue.  aAbstract expressionism.  aAda Louise Huxtable.  aAdolph Gottlieb.  aAlexander Calder.  aAlexander Liberman.  aAlexander Stirling Calder.  aAline B. Saarinen.  aAnish Kapoor.  aArchitectural Design.  aArchitectural Forum.  aArchitectural Record.  aArchitectural firm.  aArchitectural historian.  aAtomic Age.  aBlack Mountain College.  aBuckminster Fuller.  aCharles Sheeler.  aCharles and Ray Eames.  aClaes Olden